					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">An Essay of Hope and Justice to the American People</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=493812" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <blockquote>
<p>
This essay was originally a school assignment that I expanded. So far it has reached as for as the Washington Post and other local news-papers of the Maryland/DC area. I have to admit that it took about 3 hours of editing and I had to stop every 10-15 minutes so I could let out some tears. I hope you like my essay.</p>
<i><p>
How can people be this mad to do these attacks? A few days ago, a horrific act of terrorism struck the hearts of many American citizens. Two of some of the most respected and valuable buildings in the world were destroyed. The nerve center of the US Army and Navy were damaged. Although much lost, some good things can come from this disaster. The terrorists most likely wanted America to shut down airports, tighten security to create a fear of flying, cancel sports events and most of all a destroy the economy. Also, even if things such as the stock market closing, buildings collapsed, tens of thousands of jobs lost, one of the most favorite citiess in the US turned to a war zone, hope must not be given up. There are so many things that we can do to help get the United States back together.</p>
<p>
The first major task is that we all must come together and unite, which most of us are doing now. Before these attacks, there was so much violence, poverty, and crime in the US already. Now, we are coming forth as one country to show that we have freedom. Donations must be made to family’s that have lost loved ones and tributes to hospitals should occur. One thing the terrorists wanted was for the stock market/economy to go down. To backfire this plan, large money holders should buy huge amounts of stock to bring the economy back up. Not only will they be helping the country they will get all those stocks! Finally, memorials should be given and we can never forget the tragedy that has occurred. However, much worse things could happen from this that we can change.</p>
<p>
Personally, I think the terrorists wanted to change our lives and to put fear in us. The first thing we have to do is get back on the airplanes. Also, we must show that we can have good security and face our fears. We must help our neighbor, to recover from a loss and to encourage them to go back to work. A time of mourning is necessary, but a year of depression is not. America is a known for its freedom, which supposedly is lost. We must not lose our freedom. Although it was attacked, we must always defend it. Our flag still stands for freedom for they cannot take that away. Great leaps in friendship could occur sooner or later. We must show the world that we are not terrorized because we have heaven on our side. We will stand by as American’s.</p>
<p>
The last dreadful causes of these attacks are the retaliation efforts. I understand that we want to get rid of Osama Ben Laden, but we do not want to turn into the murderers that we have encountered. If we bomb, raid, or nuke any country, we will be killing many innocent people. We must not show that we are becoming evil, for that is what they wanted from us also. We must never fight fire with fire because two wrongs don’t make a right. We can learn by doing these actions, and find a legitimate way to deal with our problems.</p>
<p>
Why did these things happen we could never know? If it’s great buildings destroyed, lives lost, a damaged economy, or the tampering with our lives, we can never give up. Although good things can become of this, many sad events have occurred. The most important thing we can do right now is to become one and get through one of the most toughest things in American history. If we do accomplish this task, in 50 to 100 years we can pass along to our children and grand-children information about this past couple of days. Of how America came through this and can still remain a great nation.</p></i>
<p>
If you would like to contact me e-mail me at <a HREF="HTTP://mailto:Axhelm@hotmail.com"              >Axhelm@hotmail.com</a></p>
<p>
Brian Hendricks<br>
8th Grader at Mclean School of Maryland<br>
A boy with a broken heart and a shattered dream.</p>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
