	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				&quot;They have unleashed the Dogs of War without a leash, and that in my opinion is a very stupid thing to do.&quot; -Pith<BR>
<BR>
They're unleashed without a leash...?  Um.  Okay.  <BR>
<BR>
I could've had some great fun with that.  Too bad someone beat me to it.<BR>
<BR>
Anyway, people are up in arms talking about how America is suddenly so hot for war...Need I remind you that we were the ones who were going about our daily business only to look up and see a beautiful day suddenly  go straight to hell when some 5 thousand or so people were brutally slaughtered?  We might answer the call to war, but we are NOT the ones who caused it.<BR>
<BR>
Whatever the U.S. might have done or not done, it has done the best it knew to do.  We can't please every one, and when we do things that help or please one country, undoubtedly, we are going to piss another country off.  But does that justify the murder of thousands of innocents?  And I'm sick and tired of hearing about the things that America doesn't fix.  We can do a great deal, and so we do, but still, we can NOT fix everything, and the only things that the world ever sees is what we don't fix or the harm we cause.  It's as though one misdeed negates all the good we do.  There are a lot of people in this world who would be 10 times worse off than they would be without U.S. aid or intervention.  But the world would rather have its cake and eat it to.  You want us to fix problems caused you by another people or country, but when you are the one CAUSING the problem, you want us to butt out.  <BR>
<BR>
And DONT throw Nagasaki or Hiroshimi in our face again.  I've heard that comparison far too many times of late.  Again, we did not wake up one morning and go 'Hey, I think I'll bomb Japan today and kill as many people as I can'.  We were attacked first.  People are blaming us for WWII, when it is a fact of history that we tried our damnedest to avoid getting involved.  Japan took it upon itself to drag us into it by attacking Pearl Harbor.  Then, and ONLY then, did we launch our attack.  And when Japan didn't listen to the first bomb, that's when we dropped our second one.  It was a hard decision, and a cruel one, but it was made clear that we had no choice.<BR>
<BR>
As for this.  I don't give a damn what bin Laden's reasons are for his assault.  History has shown that however people of his calibre begin, sooner or later, they get stars in their eyes...read, world domination.  Hitler ring a bell? How 'bout Napolean?  Or Hussein?  Even if bin Laden has understandable reasons to hate the U.S., the murder of 5000+ people was unacceptable as retaliation for our 'sins'.  And if it goes unanswered, it will not stop with that attack.  Nor will it stop with the United States.<BR>
<BR>
Never fails.  When things are going bad, they praise us for giving them a hand.  Soon's things start going good, any U.S. presence is seen as 'meddlesome'.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
