				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				In a more simple form:<BR>
<BR>
Bin Ladin resisted his court summons and now they are planning to arrest him.  Anyone who gets in the way of his arrest will be arrested.  If they try to hurt the people arresting them.. the &quot;police&quot; have a right to fight back, possibly killing them.  <BR>
<BR>
When the U.S. embassy was first attacked it gave the US permission to look into the terrorist goings-on within the country that the embassy is in.  The US started to research stuff as a result.  People considered this research and discussion about ending this stuff back then to be &quot;medling in foreign affairs&quot;.  Later a US ship was destroyed.. once again the US researched whatever involvment there was in that event.. if they tried to progress any further that would be considered once again.. &quot;medling&quot;...<BR>
Now... with 3 bombings on the US at one time.. the US has said enough.. whether we are &quot;medling&quot; or not we are going to bring a stop to this thing in any way we can because it is not only harming others but now it is spreading.. and this we cannot allow.   <BR>
&quot;Medling&quot; is frowned upon the world over and in order to keep the US foreign tiesopen the US has had to hold back on its instinct.. which was to end this thing a while back.  Now there is nothing to hold the US back from seeking out the &quot;enemy&quot; and holding it responsible.  <BR>
So far as the &quot;leash&quot; thing goes.. the leash has not been removed.  If it were, the entire US would become a place under &quot;military law&quot; and every citizen would be involved in the military somehow.  As it stands there are still &quot;civilians&quot; within the US and there are no actions being taken to change that.  <BR>
<BR>

